  SUSE Linux Enterprise Server 15 SP7
  
  # Running Podman in Rootless Mode
  
  Publication Date: 21 May 2026
  
  WHAT?
  
  Everything you need to know about using rootless containers with Podman.
  
  
  WHY?
  
  Using Podman in rootless mode makes managing containers more
  efficient and secure.
  
  
  EFFORT
  
  Approximately 20 minutes of reading time.
  
  
  GOAL
  
  Understand how to configure, use and troubleshoot rootless containers with Podman.
  
  
  REQUIREMENTS
  
  - A SUSE Linux Enterprise Server system with Podman installed.
  
  
  - Working knowledge of Podman.
  
  
  
  [Revision History: Running Podman in Rootless Mode](https://documentation.suse.com/smart/container/html/rootless-podman/rh-podman-changelog.html)
  
  ## 1 Rootless Podman on SUSE Linux Enterprise [\#](https://documentation.suse.com/smart/container/html/rootless-podman/index.html\#rootless-podman-sle "Permalink")
  
  [Report an issue](https://bugzilla.suse.com/enter_bug.cgi?&amp;product=SUSE%20Linux%20Enterprise%20Server%2016.0&amp;component=Documentation&amp;short_desc=%5Bdoc%5D%20Issue%20in%20%22Rootless%20Podman%20on%20SUSE%20Linux%20Enterprise%22&amp;comment=Rootless%20Podman%20on%20SUSE%20Linux%20Enterprise%3A%0A%0Ahttps%3A%2F%2Fdocumentation.suse.com%2Fsmart%2Fcontainer%2Fhtml%2Frootless-podman%2Findex.html%23rootless-podman-sle&amp;assigned_to=dmitri.popov%40suse.com "Report an issue")
  
  Podman is the default container management and orchestration tool on SUSE Linux Enterprise. In addition to providing a drop-in replacement for Docker Open Source Engine, Podman offers several advantages, including the ability to run containers in rootless mode. This allows regular users to deploy containers without elevated privileges. In other words, rootless mode means that you can deploy a container without becoming `root` or using `sudo`.
  
  
  By default, Podman launches containers as the current regular user.
  Support for rootless containers is enabled for all newly created users in
  SLE by default, and no additional steps are necessary.
  
  
  ![Note](https://documentation.suse.com/smart/container/html/rootless-podman/static/images/icon-note.svg)
  
  Note: Data storage for rootless containers
  
  When working with container images and containers as a regular user, all relevant data is stored in `$HOME/.local/share/containers/storage` instead of `/var/lib/containers`. Make sure that the home directory has enough storage space to accommodate the data.
  
  
  ## 2 When to use rootless containers [\#](https://documentation.suse.com/smart/container/html/rootless-podman/index.html\#rootless-podman-usecases "Permalink")
  
  [Report an issue](https://bugzilla.suse.com/enter_bug.cgi?&amp;product=SUSE%20Linux%20Enterprise%20Server%2016.0&amp;component=Documentation&amp;short_desc=%5Bdoc%5D%20Issue%20in%20%22When%20to%20use%20rootless%20containers%22&amp;comment=When%20to%20use%20rootless%20containers%3A%0A%0Ahttps%3A%2F%2Fdocumentation.suse.com%2Fsmart%2Fcontainer%2Fhtml%2Frootless-podman%2Findex.html%23rootless-podman-usecases&amp;assigned_to=dmitri.popov%40suse.com "Report an issue")
  
  Improved security is the key advantage of using rootless containers. Similar to regular users, rootless containers cannot access and manipulate resources that require `root` privileges. This safeguards the host system from malicious processes running within rootless containers.
  
  
  Because running containers in rootless mode provides better security and normally does not require any additional configuration, use it as the default method of deploying containers in most situations.
  
  
  A typical scenario for rootless containers would be running a development environment based on a Language Stack SLE Base Container Image. As long as the development environment does not require write access to the system files on the host, you can run it as a rootless container.
  
  
  Rootless containers also make it possible for multiple regular users to run containers on the same machine. This can be particularly useful for deploying containers in high-performance computing environments.
  
  
  ## 3 When not to use rootless containers [\#](https://documentation.suse.com/smart/container/html/rootless-podman/index.html\#rootless-podman-limitations "Permalink")
  
  [Report an issue](https://bugzilla.suse.com/enter_bug.cgi?&amp;product=SUSE%20Linux%20Enterprise%20Server%2016.0&amp;component=Documentation&amp;short_desc=%5Bdoc%5D%20Issue%20in%20%22When%20not%20to%20use%20rootless%20containers%22&amp;comment=When%20not%20to%20use%20rootless%20containers%3A%0A%0Ahttps%3A%2F%2Fdocumentation.suse.com%2Fsmart%2Fcontainer%2Fhtml%2Frootless-podman%2Findex.html%23rootless-podman-limitations&amp;assigned_to=dmitri.popov%40suse.com "Report an issue")
  
  Although Podman makes it easy to run containers in rootless mode, there
  are scenarios, such as those listed below, where that is not an option.
  
  
  - You need the container to have write access to the host's file system.
  For example, you need to launch a container using a database dump
  stored in `/var/lib/postgresql` and being able to
  write data to it.
  
  
  - You need to bind the container to a port lower than 1024, without
  reconfiguring sysctl.
  
  
  
  ![Note](https://documentation.suse.com/smart/container/html/rootless-podman/static/images/icon-note.svg)
  
  Note: Rootless containers and slirp4netns
  
  Because unprivileged users cannot configure network namespaces on
  Linux, Podman relies on a user space network implementation called
  `slirp4netns`. It emulates the full TCP-IP stack and
  can cause a heavy performance degradation for workloads relying on high
  network transfer rates. This means that rootless containers suffer from
  slow network transfers.
  
  
  If slirp4netns is not on your system, you can install it using the `zypper install slirp4netns` command.
  
  
  ## 4 Configuring rootless containers [\#](https://documentation.suse.com/smart/container/html/rootless-podman/index.html\#rootless-podman-configure-containers "Permalink")
  
  [Report an issue](https://bugzilla.suse.com/enter_bug.cgi?&amp;product=SUSE%20Linux%20Enterprise%20Server%2016.0&amp;component=Documentation&amp;short_desc=%5Bdoc%5D%20Issue%20in%20%22Configuring%20rootless%20containers%22&amp;comment=Configuring%20rootless%20containers%3A%0A%0Ahttps%3A%2F%2Fdocumentation.suse.com%2Fsmart%2Fcontainer%2Fhtml%2Frootless-podman%2Findex.html%23rootless-podman-configure-containers&amp;assigned_to=dmitri.popov%40suse.com "Report an issue")
  
  ### 4.1 Giving Podman access to ports below 1024 [\#](https://documentation.suse.com/smart/container/html/rootless-podman/index.html\#rootless-podman-configure-port-below-1024 "Permalink")
  
  [Report an issue](https://bugzilla.suse.com/enter_bug.cgi?&amp;product=SUSE%20Linux%20Enterprise%20Server%2016.0&amp;component=Documentation&amp;short_desc=%5Bdoc%5D%20Issue%20in%20%22Giving%20Podman%20access%20to%20ports%20below%201024%22&amp;comment=Giving%20Podman%20access%20to%20ports%20below%201024%3A%0A%0Ahttps%3A%2F%2Fdocumentation.suse.com%2Fsmart%2Fcontainer%2Fhtml%2Frootless-podman%2Findex.html%23rootless-podman-configure-port-below-1024&amp;assigned_to=dmitri.popov%40suse.com "Report an issue")
  
  On Linux, unprivileged users cannot open ports below port number 1024.
  This limitation also applies to Podman, so by default, rootless
  containers cannot expose ports below port number 1024. You can remove
  this limitation temporarily using the following command:
  
  
  ```
  sysctl net.ipv4.ip_unprivileged_port_start=0
  ```
  
  Copy
  
  To remove the limitation permanently, run `sysctl -w
        net.ipv4.ip_unprivileged_port_start=0`.
  
  
  Note that this allows **all** unprivileged
  applications to bind to ports below 1024.
  
  
  ### 4.2 Using cgroups v2 [\#](https://documentation.suse.com/smart/container/html/rootless-podman/index.html\#rootless-podman-configure-cgroups-v2 "Permalink")
  
  [Report an issue](https://bugzilla.suse.com/enter_bug.cgi?&amp;product=SUSE%20Linux%20Enterprise%20Server%2016.0&amp;component=Documentation&amp;short_desc=%5Bdoc%5D%20Issue%20in%20%22Using%20cgroups%20v2%22&amp;comment=Using%20cgroups%20v2%3A%0A%0Ahttps%3A%2F%2Fdocumentation.suse.com%2Fsmart%2Fcontainer%2Fhtml%2Frootless-podman%2Findex.html%23rootless-podman-configure-cgroups-v2&amp;assigned_to=dmitri.popov%40suse.com "Report an issue")
  
  When using rootless containers with Podman, it is recommended to use
  cgroups v2. cgroups v1 have limited functionality compared to v2. For
  example, cgroups v1 do not allow proper hierarchical delegation to the
  user's subtrees. Additionally, Podman is unable to read container logs
  properly with cgroups v1 and the systemd log driver.
  
  
  To find out which cgroups version is default on your system, use the
  following command:
  
  
  ```markdown
  > mount|grep ^cgroup|awk '{print $1}'|uniq
  cgroup2
  cgroup
  ```
  
  Copy
  
  The first entry in the output indicates the default cgroups version.
  
  
  If you are using a version of SUSE Linux Enterprise Server with cgroups v1, you can
  enable cgroups v2 by adding the following to the kernel cmdline:
  `systemd.unified_cgroup_hierarchy=1`. Then update GRUB
  using the `grub2-mkconfig -o /boot/grub2/grub.cfg`
  command.
  
  
  Even on setups of SUSE Linux Enterprise Server with cgroup v2, the default
  configuration delegates no controllers to user sessions
  (for performance reasons) and chosen controllers should be enabled explicitly,
  [https://documentation.suse.com/sles/single-html/SLES-tuning/#sec-cgroups-user-sessions](https://documentation.suse.com/sles/single-html/SLES-tuning/#sec-cgroups-user-sessions).
  
  
  ### 4.3 Enabling read access to the SUSE Customer Center credentials [\#](https://documentation.suse.com/smart/container/html/rootless-podman/index.html\#rootless-podman-troubleshoot-read-access "Permalink")
  
  [Report an issue](https://bugzilla.suse.com/enter_bug.cgi?&amp;product=SUSE%20Linux%20Enterprise%20Server%2016.0&amp;component=Documentation&amp;short_desc=%5Bdoc%5D%20Issue%20in%20%22Enabling%20read%20access%20to%20the%20SUSE%20Customer%20Center%20credentials%22&amp;comment=Enabling%20read%20access%20to%20the%20SUSE%20Customer%20Center%20credentials%3A%0A%0Ahttps%3A%2F%2Fdocumentation.suse.com%2Fsmart%2Fcontainer%2Fhtml%2Frootless-podman%2Findex.html%23rootless-podman-troubleshoot-read-access&amp;assigned_to=dmitri.popov%40suse.com "Report an issue")
  
  Running a container with Podman in rootless mode on SUSE Linux Enterprise Server may fail,
  because the container needs read access to the SUSE Customer Center credentials. For
  example, running a container with the command `podman run -it
        --rm registry.suse.com/suse/sle15 bash` and then executing
  `zypper ref` results in the following error message:
  
  
  ```
  Refreshing service 'container-suseconnect-zypp'.
    Problem retrieving the repository index file for service 'container-suseconnect-zypp':
    [container-suseconnect-zypp|file:/usr/lib/zypp/plugins/services/container-suseconnect-zypp]
    Warning: Skipping service 'container-suseconnect-zypp' because of the above error.
    Warning: There are no enabled repositories defined.
    Use 'zypper addrepo' or 'zypper modifyrepo' commands to add or enable repositories
  ```
  
  Copy
  
  To solve the problem, grant the current user the required access rights
  by running the following command on the host:
  
  
  ```markdown
  > sudo setfacl -m u:$(id -nu):r /etc/zypp/credentials.d/*
  ```
  
  Copy
  
  Log out and log in again to apply the changes.
  
  
  To give multiple users the required access, create a dedicated group
  using the `groupadd
        GROUPNAME` command. Then use the
  following command to change the group ownership and rights of files in
  the `/etc/zypp/credentials.d/` directory.
  
  
  ```markdown
  > sudo chgrp GROUPNAME /etc/zypp/credentials.d/*
  > sudo chmod g+r /etc/zypp/credentials.d/*
  ```
  
  Copy
  
  You can then grant a specific user write access by adding them to the
  created group.
  
  
  ## 5 Understanding user mapping [\#](https://documentation.suse.com/smart/container/html/rootless-podman/index.html\#rootless-podman-user-mapping "Permalink")
  
  [Report an issue](https://bugzilla.suse.com/enter_bug.cgi?&amp;product=SUSE%20Linux%20Enterprise%20Server%2016.0&amp;component=Documentation&amp;short_desc=%5Bdoc%5D%20Issue%20in%20%22Understanding%20user%20mapping%22&amp;comment=Understanding%20user%20mapping%3A%0A%0Ahttps%3A%2F%2Fdocumentation.suse.com%2Fsmart%2Fcontainer%2Fhtml%2Frootless-podman%2Findex.html%23rootless-podman-user-mapping&amp;assigned_to=dmitri.popov%40suse.com "Report an issue")
  
  ### 5.1 User mapping and rootless containers [\#](https://documentation.suse.com/smart/container/html/rootless-podman/index.html\#rootless-containers-user-mapping "Permalink")
  
  [Report an issue](https://bugzilla.suse.com/enter_bug.cgi?&amp;product=SUSE%20Linux%20Enterprise%20Server%2016.0&amp;component=Documentation&amp;short_desc=%5Bdoc%5D%20Issue%20in%20%22User%20mapping%20and%20rootless%20containers%22&amp;comment=User%20mapping%20and%20rootless%20containers%3A%0A%0Ahttps%3A%2F%2Fdocumentation.suse.com%2Fsmart%2Fcontainer%2Fhtml%2Frootless-podman%2Findex.html%23rootless-containers-user-mapping&amp;assigned_to=dmitri.popov%40suse.com "Report an issue")
  
  By definition, rootless containers are run by a regular user. At the same
  time, certain applications deployed using containers expect to be run as
  root. This leads to a problem: how do you run a container as root, when
  you are not root on the host system? To solve the issue, Podman relies
  on user namespaces to map user IDs in the container to different user IDs
  on the host. By default, Podman maps the root user inside the container
  with the user ID (UID) 0 to the UID of the current user on the host system.
  
  
  To illustrate how this is done in practice, create a temporary
  SLE BCI-Base container (the `sleep` value determines for
  how long the container runs):
  
  
  ```markdown
  > podman run -d --rm registry.suse.com/bci/bci-base sleep 600
  ```
  
  Copy
  
  Then run the `podman top` command as follows:
  
  
  ```markdown
  > podman top -l user huser
  USER  HUSER
  root  1000
  ```
  
  Copy
  
  The output indicates that the root user in the container is mapped to the
  user with UID 1000 on the host, so a root process inside the container is
  treated by the kernel as UID 1000 outside the container. This means that
  even though the process is running as root inside the container, this
  process does not have root privileges outside of the container. Moreover, if a file owned by a UID, and this UID is not mapped
  into the user namespace, the file is treated as owned by
  “nobody” (UID 65534). This also means that the container
  process is not allowed to access the file, unless the file is world
  readable and writable.
  
  
  There are also situations, when a process or an application inside a
  container must run as the current host user. The
  `--userns=keep-id` option solves this problem by
  instructing Podman to map the user as itself into the container. To see
  how this works, create a temporary SLE BCI-Base container, but this time
  with `--userns=keep-id`:
  
  
  ```markdown
  > podman run -d --rm --userns=keep-id registry.suse.com/bci/bci-base sleep 600
  ```
  
  Copy
  
  Run the `podman top` again:
  
  
  ```markdown
  > podman top -l user huser
  
  USER  HUSER
  tux   tux
  ```
  
  Copy
  
  The output now shows that the regular user on the host system is mapped
  into the container.
  
  
  There is another way to see how this works in practice. First, run the
  following command:
  
  
  ```markdown
  > podman run --rm -it -v ~/Downloads/:/downloads:Z registry.suse.com/bci/bci-base:15.5 ls -al /downloads
  ```
  
  Copy
  
  The command creates a container from the SLE BCI-Base container image,
  mounts the `Downloads` directory on the host system as
  the `downloads` directory inside, and then runs the
  `ls -al` command in the `downloads`
  directory. The output of the command looks something like this:
  
  
  ```
  -rw-r--r-- 1 root root  4417088 Aug 25 09:21 document.pdf
  ```
  
  Copy
  
  This shows that the file is owned by root. Now, run the same command, but
  this time with the `--userns=keep-id` option:
  
  
  ```markdown
  > podman run --userns=keep-id --rm -it -v ~/Downloads/:/downloads:Z registry.suse.com/bci/bci-base:15.5 ls -al /downloads
  ```
  
  Copy
  
  This time, the output looks slightly different, indicating that the file
  is owned by the host user:
  
  
  ```
  -rw-r--r-- 1 tux users 4417088 Aug 25 09:21 document.pdf
  ```
  
  Copy
  
  ## 6 Troubleshooting [\#](https://documentation.suse.com/smart/container/html/rootless-podman/index.html\#rootless-podman-troubleshooting "Permalink")
  
  [Report an issue](https://bugzilla.suse.com/enter_bug.cgi?&amp;product=SUSE%20Linux%20Enterprise%20Server%2016.0&amp;component=Documentation&amp;short_desc=%5Bdoc%5D%20Issue%20in%20%22Troubleshooting%22&amp;comment=Troubleshooting%3A%0A%0Ahttps%3A%2F%2Fdocumentation.suse.com%2Fsmart%2Fcontainer%2Fhtml%2Frootless-podman%2Findex.html%23rootless-podman-troubleshooting&amp;assigned_to=dmitri.popov%40suse.com "Report an issue")
  
  ### 6.1 Rootless mode fails [\#](https://documentation.suse.com/smart/container/html/rootless-podman/index.html\#rootless-podman-troubleshoot-fix-root "Permalink")
  
  [Report an issue](https://bugzilla.suse.com/enter_bug.cgi?&amp;product=SUSE%20Linux%20Enterprise%20Server%2016.0&amp;component=Documentation&amp;short_desc=%5Bdoc%5D%20Issue%20in%20%22Rootless%20mode%20fails%22&amp;comment=Rootless%20mode%20fails%3A%0A%0Ahttps%3A%2F%2Fdocumentation.suse.com%2Fsmart%2Fcontainer%2Fhtml%2Frootless-podman%2Findex.html%23rootless-podman-troubleshoot-fix-root&amp;assigned_to=dmitri.popov%40suse.com "Report an issue")
  
  If Podman fails to launch containers in rootless mode, check
  whether an entry for the current user is present in
  `/etc/subuid` on the host system:
  
  
  ```markdown
  > grep $(id -nu) /etc/subuid
    user:10000:65536
  ```
  
  Copy
  
  When no entry is found, add the required sub-UID and sub-GID entries via
  the following command:
  
  
  ```markdown
  > sudo usermod --add-subuids 100000-165535 --add-subgids 100000-165535 $(id -nu)
  ```
  
  Copy
  
  To enable the change, reboot the machine or stop the session of the
  current user. To do the latter, run `loginctl list-sessions |
        grep USER` and note the session ID.
  Then run `loginctl kill-session
        SESSION_ID` to stop the session.
  
  
  The `usermod` command above defines a range of local
  UIDs to which the UIDs allocated to users inside the container are mapped
  on the host. Note that the ranges defined for different users must not
  overlap. It is also important that the ranges do not reuse the UID of an
  existing local user or group. By default, adding a user with the
  `useradd` command on SUSE Linux Enterprise Server automatically
  allocates sub-UID and sub-GID ranges.
  
  
  ### 6.2 Rootless containers and the storage graph root [\#](https://documentation.suse.com/smart/container/html/rootless-podman/index.html\#rootless-podman-troubleshoot-storage-graph-root "Permalink")
  
  [Report an issue](https://bugzilla.suse.com/enter_bug.cgi?&amp;product=SUSE%20Linux%20Enterprise%20Server%2016.0&amp;component=Documentation&amp;short_desc=%5Bdoc%5D%20Issue%20in%20%22Rootless%20containers%20and%20the%20storage%20graph%20root%22&amp;comment=Rootless%20containers%20and%20the%20storage%20graph%20root%3A%0A%0Ahttps%3A%2F%2Fdocumentation.suse.com%2Fsmart%2Fcontainer%2Fhtml%2Frootless-podman%2Findex.html%23rootless-podman-troubleshoot-storage-graph-root&amp;assigned_to=dmitri.popov%40suse.com "Report an issue")
  
  Podman stores the containers' data in the storage graph root (default is
  `~/.local/share/containers/storage`). Because of the
  way Podman remaps user IDs in rootless containers, the graph root may
  contain files that are not owned by your current user but by a user ID in
  the sub-UID region assigned to your user. As these files do not belong to
  your current user, they can be inaccessible to you.
  
  
  To read or modify any file in the graph root, enter a shell as follows:
  
  
  ```markdown
  > podman unshare bash
  > id
    uid=0(root) gid=0(root) groups=0(root),65534(nobody)
  ```
  
  Copy
  
  Note that `podman unshare` performs the same user
  remapping as `podman run` does when launching a rootless
  container. You cannot gain elevated privileges via `podman
        unshare`.
  
  
  ![Warning](https://documentation.suse.com/smart/container/html/rootless-podman/static/images/icon-warning.svg)
  
  Warning
  
  Do not modify files in the graph root as this can corrupt Podman's
  internal state and render your containers, images and volumes inoperable.
  
  
